name: Retinoic acid
Reason: The base unit for retinoic acid can be considered as benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5°C. Adding functional groups to the benzene will alter its melting point. The structure of retinoic acid includes several functional groups: a carboxylic acid group, several alkene groups, and an isopropyl group. Each of these groups affects the melting point differently. The carboxylic acid group has strong hydrogen bonding, significantly raising the melting point by about 100°C. The alkene groups slightly destabilize the crystalline structure, reducing the melting point; each double bond might reduce it by about -5°C. However, conjugation in the alkenes can stabilize the structure and increase the melting point, potentially adding up +5°C for each double bond due to the added rigidity and planarity. The isopropyl group contributes to the molecular weight and van der Waals interactions, raising the melting point by about 20°C. Considering there are five alkene groups, the net effect of the alkene groups might be around 0°C since destabilization and stabilization effects could cancel each other out. The predicted melting point would therefore be the sum of the effects of each of these functional groups.
